# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-commons-java
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] In computer programming, **boilerplate code**, or simply **boilerplate**, are sections of code that are repeated in multiple places with little to no variation.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] When using languages that are considered *verbose*, the programmer must write a lot of boilerplate code to accomplish only minor functionality.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] It is also possible to move boilerplate code to an *abstract class* so that it can be inherited by any number of *concrete classes*.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] Another option would be to move it into a subroutine so that it can be called instead of being duplicated.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] The term arose from the newspaper business.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] Columns and other pieces that were distributed by print syndicates were sent to subscribing newspapers in the form of prepared printing plates.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] Because of their resemblance to the metal plates used in the making of boilers, they became known as "boiler plates", and their resulting text—"boilerplate text".
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] As the stories that were distributed by boiler plates were usually "fillers" rather than "serious" news, the term became synonymous with unoriginal, repeated text.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] A related term is *bookkeeping code*, referring to code that is not part of the business logic but is interleaved with it in order to keep data structures updated or handle secondary aspects of the program.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] One form of boilerplate consists of declarations which, while not part of the program logic or the language's essential syntax, are added to the start of a source file as a matter of custom.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] The first line is a shebang, which identifies the file as a Perl script that can be executed directly on the command line on Unix/Linux systems.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] The other two are pragmas turning on warnings and strict mode, which are mandated by fashionable Perl programming style.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] This next example is a C/C++ programming language boilerplate, `#include` guard.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] This checks, and sets up, a global flag to tell the compiler whether the file myinterface.h has already been included.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] As many interdepending files may be involved in the compilation of a module, this avoids processing the same header multiple times, (which would lead to errors due to multiple definitions with the same name).
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] In Java programs, DTO classes are often provided with methods for getting and setting instance variables.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] The definitions of these methods can frequently be regarded as boilerplate.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] Although the code will vary from one class to another, it is sufficiently stereotypical in structure that it would be better generated automatically than written by hand.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] Most of the boilerplate in this example exists to fulfill requirements of JavaBeans.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] If the variables **name** and **owner** were declared as public, the accessor and mutator methods would not be needed.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] In Java 14, record classes were added to fight with this issue.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] To reduce the amount of boilerplate, many frameworks have been developed, e.g.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] In some other programming languages it may be possible to achieve the same thing with less boilerplate, when the language has built-in support for such common constructs.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] The WHATWG HTML Living Standard defines that the `<html>`, `<head>` and `<body>` tags may be safely omitted under most circumstances.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] The `<meta charset="UTF-8">` tag is technically redundant when coming directly from a web server configured to send the character encoding in an HTTP header, though it becomes useful when the HTML response is saved in an `.html` file, cache, or web archive.
[src:apache-commons-java/boilerplate-code] Google's HTML/CSS style guide recommends that all optional tags be omitted, resulting in much less boilerplate.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:apache-commons-java/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] In computing, a **library** is a collection of resources that can be used during software development to implement a computer program.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Commonly, a library consists of executable code such as compiled functions and classes, or a library can be a collection of source code.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A resource library may contain data such as images and text.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A library can be used by multiple, independent consumers (programs and other libraries).
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] This differs from resources defined in a program which can usually only be used by that program.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] When a consumer uses a library resource, it gains the value of the library without having to implement it itself.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Libraries encourage software reuse in a modular fashion.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Libraries can use other libraries resulting in a hierarchy of libraries in a program.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] When writing code that uses a library, a programmer only needs to know how to use that library's application programming interface (API) without understanding its internal mechanics.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] For example, a program could use a library that abstracts a complicated system call so that the programmer can use the system feature without spending time to learn the intricacies of the system function.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] The idea of a computer library dates back to the first computers created by Charles Babbage.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] An 1888 paper on his Analytical Engine suggested that computer operations could be punched on separate cards from numerical input.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] In 1947 Goldstine and von Neumann speculated that it would be useful to create a "library" of subroutines for their work on the IAS machine, an early computer that was not yet operational at that time.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] They envisioned a physical library of magnetic wire recordings, with each wire storing reusable computer code.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Inspired by von Neumann, Wilkes and his team constructed EDSAC.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A filing cabinet of punched tape held the subroutine library for this computer.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Programs for EDSAC consisted of a main program and a sequence of subroutines copied from the subroutine library.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] In 1951 the team published the first textbook on programming, *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, which detailed the creation and the purpose of the library.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] COBOL included "primitive capabilities for a library system" in 1959, but Jean Sammet described them as "inadequate library facilities" in retrospect.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] JOVIAL has a Communication Pool (COMPOOL), roughly a library of header files.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Another major contributor to the modern library concept came in the form of the subprogram innovation of FORTRAN.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] FORTRAN subprograms can be compiled independently of each other, but the compiler lacked a linker.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] So prior to the introduction of modules in Fortran-90, type checking between FORTRAN subprograms was impossible.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] By the mid 1960s, copy and macro libraries for assemblers were common.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Starting with the popularity of the IBM System/360, libraries containing other types of text elements, e.g., system parameters, also became common.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] In IBM's OS/360 and its successors this is called a partitioned data set.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] The first object-oriented programming language, Simula, developed in 1965, supported adding classes to libraries via its compiler.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] The *linking* (or *binding*) process resolves references known as *symbols* (or *links*) by searching for them in various locations including configured libraries.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] If a linker (or binder) does not find a symbol, then it fails, but multiple matches may or may not cause failure.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Some references in a program or library module are stored in a relative or symbolic form which cannot be resolved until all code and libraries are assigned final static addresses.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Relocation is the process of adjusting these references, and is done either by the linker or the loader.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] In general, relocation cannot be done to individual libraries themselves because the addresses in memory may vary depending on the program using them and other libraries they are combined with.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] Position-independent code avoids references to absolute addresses and therefore does not require relocation.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] An executable library consists of code that has been converted from source code into machine code or an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A linker allows for using library objects by associating each reference with an address at which the object is located.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] For example, in C, a library function is invoked via C's normal function call syntax and semantics.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A variant is a library containing compiled code (object code in IBM's nomenclature) in a form that cannot be loaded by the OS but that can be read by the linker.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A static library is an executable library that is linked into a program at build-time by a linker (or whatever the build tool is called that does linking).
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] This process, and the resulting stand-alone file, is known as a static build of the program.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A static build may not need any further relocation if virtual memory is used and no address space layout randomization is desired.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A static library is sometimes called an *archive* on Unix-like systems.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] A dynamic library is linked when the program is run – either at load-time or runtime.
[src:apache-commons-java/library-computing] The dynamic library was intended after the static library to support additional software deployment flexibility.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:apache-commons-java/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In computer programming, a **string** is traditionally a sequence of characters, either as a literal constant or as some kind of variable.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The latter may allow its elements to be mutated and the length changed, or it may be fixed (after creation).
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A string is often implemented as an array data structure of bytes (or words) that stores a sequence of elements, typically characters, using some character encoding.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] More general, *string* may also denote a sequence (or list) of data other than just characters.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Depending on the programming language and precise data type used, a variable declared to be a string may either cause storage in memory to be statically allocated for a predetermined maximum length or employ dynamic allocation to allow it to hold a variable number of elements.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] When a string appears literally in source code, it is known as a string literal or an anonymous string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In formal languages, which are used in mathematical logic and theoretical computer science, a string is a finite sequence of symbols that are chosen from a set called an alphabet.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A primary purpose of strings is to store human-readable text, like words and sentences.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Strings are used to communicate information from a computer program to the user of the program.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A program may also accept string input from its user.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Further, strings may store data expressed as characters yet not intended for human reading.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The term string may also designate a sequence of data or computer records other than characters — like a "string of bits" — but when used without qualification it refers to strings of characters.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Use of the word "string" to mean any items arranged in a line, series or succession dates back centuries.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In 19th-century typesetting, compositors used the term "string" to denote a length of type printed on paper; the string would be measured to determine the compositor's pay.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Use of the word "string" to mean "a sequence of symbols or linguistic elements in a definite order" emerged from mathematics, symbolic logic, and linguistic theory to speak about the formal behavior of symbolic systems, setting aside the symbols' meaning.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Sammet, "the first realistic string handling and pattern matching language" for computers was COMIT in the 1950s, followed by the SNOBOL language of the early 1960s.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A **string datatype** is a datatype modeled on the idea of a formal string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Strings are such an important and useful datatype that they are implemented in nearly every programming language.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In some languages they are available as primitive types and in others as composite types.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The syntax of most high-level programming languages allows for a string, usually quoted in some way, to represent an instance of a string datatype; such a meta-string is called a *literal* or *string literal*.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Although formal strings can have an arbitrary finite length, the length of strings in real languages is often constrained to an artificial maximum.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Most strings in modern programming languages are variable-length strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Of course, even variable-length strings are limited in length by the amount of available memory.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The string length can be stored as a separate integer (which may put another artificial limit on the length) or implicitly through a termination character, usually a character value with all bits zero such as in C programming language.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] These character sets were typically based on ASCII or EBCDIC.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] If text in one encoding was displayed on a system using a different encoding, text was often mangled, though often somewhat readable and some computer users learned to read the mangled text.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Logographic languages such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean (known collectively as CJK) need far more than 256 characters (the limit of a one 8-bit byte per-character encoding) for reasonable representation.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The normal solutions involved keeping single-byte representations for ASCII and using two-byte representations for CJK ideographs.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Use of these with existing code led to problems with matching and cutting of strings, the severity of which depended on how the character encoding was designed.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Some encodings such as the EUC family guarantee that a byte value in the ASCII range will represent only that ASCII character, making the encoding safe for systems that use those characters as field separators.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Other encodings such as ISO-2022 and Shift-JIS do not make such guarantees, making matching on byte codes unsafe.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] These encodings also were not "self-synchronizing", so that locating character boundaries required backing up to the start of a string, and pasting two strings together could result in corruption of the second string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Unicode has simplified the picture somewhat.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Most programming languages now have a datatype for Unicode strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Unicode's preferred byte stream format UTF-8 is designed not to have the problems described above for older multibyte encodings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Some languages, such as C++, Perl and Ruby, normally allow the contents of a string to be changed after it has been created; these are termed *mutable* strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In other languages, such as Java, JavaScript, Lua, Python, and Go, the value is fixed and a new string must be created if any alteration is to be made; these are termed *immutable* strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Some of these languages with immutable strings also provide another type that is mutable, such as Java and .NET's `StringBuilder`, the thread-safe Java `StringBuffer`, and the Cocoa `NSMutableString`.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Immutability brings advantages and disadvantages: while immutable strings may require inefficiently creating many copies, they are simpler and fully thread-safe.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Strings are typically implemented as arrays of bytes, characters, or code units, to allow fast access to individual units or substrings, including characters when they have a fixed length.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A few languages such as Haskell implement them as linked lists instead.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Many high-level languages provide strings as a primitive data type, such as JavaScript and PHP, while most others provide them as a composite data type, some with special language support in writing literals, for example, Java and C#.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Some languages, such as C, Prolog and Erlang, avoid implementing a dedicated string datatype at all, instead adopting the convention of representing strings as lists of character codes.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Even in programming languages having a dedicated string type, strings can usually be iterated as a sequence of character codes, like lists of integers or other values.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Representations of strings depend heavily on the choice of character repertoire and the method of character encoding.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Older string implementations were designed to work with repertoire and encoding defined by ASCII, or more recent extensions like the ISO 8859 series.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Modern implementations often use the extensive repertoire defined by Unicode along with a variety of complex encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The term *byte string* usually indicates a general-purpose string of bytes, rather than strings of only (readable) characters, strings of bits, or such.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Byte strings often imply that bytes can take any value and any data can be stored as-is, meaning that there should be no value interpreted as a termination value.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Most string implementations are very similar to variable-length arrays with the entries storing the character codes of corresponding characters.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The principal difference is that, with certain encodings, a single logical character may take up more than one entry in the array.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This happens, for example, with UTF-8, where single codes (UCS code points) can take anywhere from one to four bytes, and single characters can take an arbitrary number of codes.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In these cases, the logical length of the string (number of characters) differs from the physical length of the array (number of bytes in use).
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] UTF-32 avoids the first part of the problem.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The length of a string can be stored in a dope vector, separate from the storage holding the actual characters.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The IBM PL/I (F) compiler used a **string dope vector** (SDV) for variable-length strings and for passing string parameters.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The SDV contains a current length and a maximum length, and is not adjacent to the string proper.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] After PL/I (F), IBM dropped the SDV in favor of length-prefixed strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The length of a string can be stored implicitly by using a special terminating character; often this is the null character (NUL), which has all bits zero, a convention used and perpetuated by the popular C programming language.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Hence, this representation is commonly referred to as a **C string**.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This representation of an *n*-character string takes *n* + 1 space (1 for the terminator), and is thus an implicit data structure.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In terminated strings, the terminating code is not an allowable character in any string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Strings with *length* field do not have this limitation and can also store arbitrary binary data.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The length of the string in the above example, "`FRANK`", is 5 characters, but it occupies 6 bytes.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Characters after the terminator do not form part of the representation; they may be either part of other data or just garbage.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Using a special byte other than null for terminating strings has historically appeared in both hardware and software, though sometimes with a value that was also a printing character.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] `$` was used by many assembler systems, `:` used by CDC systems (this character had a value of zero), and the ZX80 used `"` since this was the string delimiter in its BASIC language.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Somewhat similar, "data processing" machines like the IBM 1401 used a special word mark bit to delimit strings at the left, where the operation would start at the right.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This bit had to be clear in all other parts of the string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This meant that, while the IBM 1401 had a seven-bit word, almost no-one ever thought to use this as a feature, and override the assignment of the seventh bit to (for example) handle ASCII codes.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Early microcomputer software relied upon the fact that ASCII codes do not use the high-order bit, and set it to indicate the end of a string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The length of a string can also be stored explicitly, for example by prefixing the string with the length as a byte value.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This convention is used in many Pascal dialects; as a consequence, some people call such a string a **Pascal string** or **P-string**.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Storing the string length as byte limits the maximum string length to 255.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] To avoid such limitations, improved implementations of P-strings use 16-, 32-, or 64-bit words to store the string length.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] When the *length* field covers the address space, strings are limited only by the available memory.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] If the length is not bounded, encoding a length *n* takes log(*n*) space (see fixed-length code), so length-prefixed strings are a succinct data structure, encoding a string of length *n* in log(*n*) + *n* space.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In the latter case, the length-prefix field itself does not have fixed length, therefore the actual string data needs to be moved when the string grows such that the length field needs to be increased.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] However, since the implementation is usually hidden, the string must be accessed and modified through member functions.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] `text` is a pointer to a dynamically allocated memory area, which might be expanded as needed.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Both character termination and length codes limit strings: For example, C character arrays that contain null (NUL) characters cannot be handled directly by C string library functions: Strings using a length code are limited to the maximum value of the length code.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Both of these limitations can be overcome by clever programming.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] It is possible to create data structures and functions that manipulate them that do not have the problems associated with character termination and can in principle overcome length code bounds.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] It is also possible to optimize the string represented using techniques from run length encoding (replacing repeated characters by the character value and a length) and Hamming encoding.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] While these representations are common, others are possible.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Using ropes makes certain string operations, such as insertions, deletions, and concatenations more efficient.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The differing memory layout and storage requirements of strings can affect the security of the program accessing the string data.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] String representations requiring a terminating character are commonly susceptible to buffer overflow problems if the terminating character is not present, caused by a coding error or an attacker deliberately altering the data.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] String representations adopting a separate length field are also susceptible if the length can be manipulated.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In such cases, program code accessing the string data requires bounds checking to ensure that it does not inadvertently access or change data outside of the string memory limits.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] String data is frequently obtained from user input to a program.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] As such, it is the responsibility of the program to validate the string to ensure that it represents the expected format.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Performing limited or no validation of user input can cause a program to be vulnerable to code injection attacks.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Sometimes, strings need to be embedded inside a text file that is both human-readable and intended for consumption by a machine.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This is needed in, for example, source code of programming languages, or in configuration files.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In this case, the NUL character does not work well as a terminator since it is normally invisible (non-printable) and is difficult to input via a keyboard.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Storing the string length would also be inconvenient as manual computation and tracking of the length is tedious and error-prone.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] While character strings are very common uses of strings, a string in computer science may refer generically to any sequence of homogeneously typed data.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A bit string or byte string, for example, may be used to represent non-textual binary data retrieved from a communications medium.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This data may or may not be represented by a string-specific datatype, depending on the needs of the application, the desire of the programmer, and the capabilities of the programming language being used.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] If the programming language's string implementation is not 8-bit clean, data corruption may ensue.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] C programmers draw a sharp distinction between a "string", aka a "string of characters", which by definition is always null terminated, vs. an "array of characters" which may be stored in the same array but is often not null terminated.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Using C string handling functions on such an array of characters often seems to work, but later leads to security problems.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] There are many algorithms for processing strings, each with various trade-offs.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Competing algorithms can be analyzed with respect to run time, storage requirements, and so forth.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The name **stringology** was coined in 1984 by computer scientist Zvi Galil for the theory of algorithms and data structures used for string processing.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Advanced string algorithms often employ complex mechanisms and data structures, among them suffix trees and finite-state machines.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Character strings are such a useful datatype that several languages have been designed in order to make string processing applications easy to write.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Many Unix utilities perform simple string manipulations and can be used to easily program some powerful string processing algorithms.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Files and finite streams may be viewed as strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Some APIs like Multimedia Control Interface, embedded SQL or printf use strings to hold commands that will be interpreted.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Many scripting programming languages, including Perl, Python, Ruby, and Tcl employ regular expressions to facilitate text operations.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Perl is particularly noted for its regular expression use, and many other languages and applications implement Perl compatible regular expressions.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Some languages such as Perl and Ruby support string interpolation, which permits arbitrary expressions to be evaluated and included in string literals.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] String functions are used to create strings or change the contents of a mutable string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] They also are used to query information about a string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The set of functions and their names varies depending on the computer programming language.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The most basic example of a string function is the string length function – the function that returns the length of a string (not counting any terminator characters or any of the string's internal structural information) and does not modify the string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This function is often named `length`, `len`, or `size`.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] For example, `length("hello world")` would return 11.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Another common function is concatenation, where a new string is created by appending two strings, often this is the + addition operator.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Some microprocessor's instruction set architectures contain direct support for string operations, such as block copy (e.g.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Let $\Sigma$ be a finite set of distinct, unambiguous symbols (alternatively called characters), called the alphabet.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A **string** (or **word** or **expression**) over $\Sigma$ is any finite sequence of symbols from $\Sigma$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The *length* of a string s is the number of symbols in s (the length of the sequence) and can be any non-negative integer; it is often denoted as $|s|$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The *empty string* is the unique string over $\Sigma$ of length 0 , and is denoted $\varepsilon$ or $\lambda$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The set of all strings over $\Sigma$ of length n is denoted $\Sigma ^{n}$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] We have $\Sigma ^{0}=\{\varepsilon \}$ for every alphabet $\Sigma$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The set of all strings over $\Sigma$ of any length is the Kleene closure of $\Sigma$ and is denoted $\Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Although the set $\Sigma ^{*}$ itself is countably infinite, each element of $\Sigma ^{*}$ is a string of finite length.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A set of strings over $\Sigma$ (i.e. any subset of $\Sigma ^{*}$ ) is called a *formal language* over $\Sigma$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] String concatenation is an associative, but non-commutative operation.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The empty string $\varepsilon$ serves as the identity element; for any string s , $\varepsilon s=s\varepsilon =s$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Therefore, the set $\Sigma ^{*}$ and the concatenation operation form a monoid, the free monoid generated by $\Sigma$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] In addition, the length function defines a monoid homomorphism from $\Sigma ^{*}$ to the non-negative integers (that is, a function $L:\Sigma ^{*}\mapsto \mathbb {N} \cup \{0\}$ , such that $L(st)=L(s)+L(t)\quad \forall s,t\in \Sigma ^{*}$ ).
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A string s is said to be a *substring* or *factor* of t if there exist (possibly empty) strings u and v such that $t=usv$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The relation "is a substring of" defines a partial order on $\Sigma ^{*}$ , the least element of which is the empty string.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A string s is said to be a prefix of t if there exists a string u such that $t=su$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] If u is nonempty, s is said to be a *proper* prefix of t .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Symmetrically, a string s is said to be a suffix of t if there exists a string u such that $t=us$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] If u is nonempty, s is said to be a *proper* suffix of t .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Suffixes and prefixes are substrings of t .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Both the relations "is a prefix of" and "is a suffix of" are prefix orders.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The reverse of a string is a string with the same symbols but in reverse order.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] For example, if $s={\texttt {abc}}$ (where ${\texttt {a}}$ , ${\texttt {b}}$ , and ${\texttt {c}}$ are symbols of the alphabet), then the reverse of s is ${\texttt {cba}}$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A string that is the reverse of itself (e.g., $s={\texttt {madam}}$ ) is called a palindrome, which also includes the empty string and all strings of length 1 .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A string $s=uv$ is said to be a rotation of t if $t=vu$ .
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] It is often useful to define an ordering on a set of strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] If the alphabet $\Sigma$ has a total order (cf. alphabetical order) one can define a total order on $\Sigma ^{*}$ called lexicographical order.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The lexicographical order is total if the alphabetical order is, but is not well-founded for any nontrivial alphabet, even if the alphabetical order is.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] See Shortlex for an alternative string ordering that preserves well-foundedness.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] A number of additional operations on strings commonly occur in the formal theory.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] These are given in the article on string operations.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] The natural topology on the set of fixed-length strings or variable-length strings is the discrete topology, but the natural topology on the set of infinite strings is the limit topology, viewing the set of infinite strings as the inverse limit of the sets of finite strings.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] This is the construction used for the *p*-adic numbers and some constructions of the Cantor set, and yields the same topology.
[src:apache-commons-java/string-computer-science] Isomorphisms between string representations of topologies can be found by normalizing according to the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] A utility may be a distinct program, or multiple utilities are implemented in a single program.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] For example, BusyBox implements many utilities in a single program.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Commonly, a utility provides a command-line interface, but some provide a graphical user interface.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Although an operating system (OS) installation usually includes utilities (which are considered part of the OS), users often install additional utilities.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] The additional utilities may provide a better user experience or additional functionality.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Often, a user must be authorized for elevated privileges to use a utility since it may affect other users of the system.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] This section is a taxonomy of kinds of utilities.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Grants or denies requests for access to system resources.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Provides for programming-level control of program execution including the examination and modification of program data.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Determines and reports the operational status of computer hardware and software.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Analyzes the host system's network connectivity, configures network settings, reports data transfer and log events.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Configures, installs and updates software on the host system.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] by removing old registry keys that are no longer in use.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Monitors resources and performance of the host system.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Reports information about installed software and hardware.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] , file corruption or accidental deletion.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] the content of a disk, increasing the capacity of the disk.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Writes to a disk so that it can be used for a particular format.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Can prepare a disk for initial use or erase the entire disk.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Divides an disk into multiple logical drives, each with its own file system which can be mounted by the operating system.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Visualizes disk space use for each file and directory.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Supports recovering files that were deleted.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Outputs a stream or a single file when provided with a directory or a set of files.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] may include compression and encryption capabilities.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Some archive utilities have a separate un-archive utility for the reverse operation.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Encrypts and decrypts streams and files.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Outputs a shorter stream or a smaller file when provided with a stream or file.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Establishes consistency among data from a source to a target data storage and vice versa.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Deletes files that are unnecessary to computer operation, or take up considerable amounts of space.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Provides an interface for performing file management tasks such as deleting, renaming, cataloging, moving, copying, merging, setting file access, creating and modifying directories.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Maintains consistency between two storages for various purposes including redundancy and backup.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Creates a file of test data according to specified patterns.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Allows for editing the data of a file without regard its format.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] programs, usually applications programs, for use in a specific computer environment.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Permits use of keyboard macros in programs that do not natively support such a feature.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Modifies files, especially object programs when program source is unavailable.
[src:apache-commons-java/utility-software] Arranges records (usually lines) of a file into a specified sequence.
